        Multiple Offers When Selling Your Brisbane Property: How to Handle Them Well
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Multiple offers is a strong position to be in. But how you handle them determines whether you achieve a good result or an excellent one.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Receiving multiple offers on your property is one of those situations sellers hope for and occasionally underestimate when it arrives. It feels straightforward: you have competing buyers, so you pick the best offer and proceed. In practice, the process is more nuanced than that, and how you handle it can make a material difference to your final result. It can also create legal exposure if managed carelessly.</p>

      <p>Multiple offer situations are common in Brisbane's inner-east suburbs, particularly for well-located family homes in Morningside, Camp Hill, Coorparoo, Bulimba, and Hawthorne. When a property is priced correctly, presented well, and launched with strong marketing, it is not unusual for two, three, or more buyers to reach offers at the same time. Understanding what your options are before you get there puts you in a far stronger position.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When multiple offers arise and what drives them</h2>
      <p>Multiple offers typically emerge when a property is priced at or slightly below where serious buyer demand sits, has been presented in a way that appeals broadly to the market, and has attracted enough campaign exposure to reach all active buyers in that bracket at once. Strong results follow from this alignment. The inverse is also true: an overpriced property or one with limited campaign reach will often attract no offers or a single low offer, regardless of actual buyer interest.</p>

      <p>In Brisbane's inner east, school catchment zones are a persistent driver of competitive interest. Properties within the Bulimba State School, Cannon Hill Anglican College, or Coorparoo State School catchments regularly attract buyers who have been watching specifically for the right home in the right zone for months. These buyers are often motivated and financially prepared, which means they move quickly when a suitable property launches. Infrastructure upgrades, proximity to the river, and walkability to dining and retail precincts on Oxford Street, Riding Road, and Old Cleveland Road also concentrate buyer demand in specific locations within suburbs.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Your legal position when multiple offers are submitted</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, you are not legally required to inform any buyer that competing offers exist. Your agent can choose to tell buyers there are other offers in play, to create urgency or encourage buyers to submit their strongest position, but there is no obligation to do so. What matters is that whatever disclosure approach is taken is applied consistently and not used to mislead buyers about the nature of their competition.</p>

      <p>Once you sign a contract with a buyer, you are legally bound. You cannot continue negotiating with other buyers or accept a better offer once a signed contract is in place with one party. The Queensland REIQ contract becomes binding on execution by both parties. This means the decision about which offer to accept, and when to sign, needs to be made carefully. Signing prematurely with one buyer and then accepting a better offer from another is not an option under Queensland property law.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Different approaches to managing the process</h2>
      <p>There is no single correct method for handling multiple offers. The right approach depends on how many buyers are involved, how strong the offers are relative to your expectations, and how confident you are in each buyer's ability to settle. The three most common approaches are sequential negotiation, a best and final deadline process, and a deadline or expression of interest campaign structure set up before launch.</p>

      <p>Sequential negotiation means working with offers one at a time, starting with the strongest, and moving to others if negotiations break down. It works well when one offer is clearly superior and you want to close it out without creating a competitive atmosphere that might backfire. The risk is that other buyers may withdraw while you negotiate, particularly if the process takes several days.</p>

      <p>A best and final process involves informing all interested buyers that there are competing offers and asking each to submit their highest and best position by a specific deadline. The seller then reviews all offers simultaneously and accepts the strongest. This approach can drive prices higher, but it is not always appropriate: some buyers dislike the process and withdraw, and if your strongest buyer walks away, you may end up with a lower result than a direct negotiation would have produced.</p>

      <p>A structured deadline campaign such as an expressions of interest process or private treaty with a closing date is often set up before launch, which avoids the awkwardness of announcing a multi-offer process mid-campaign. Buyers know from the outset that there is a set timeframe, which focuses their attention and encourages serious buyers to engage promptly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to evaluate offers beyond price</h2>
      <p>Price is the most obvious measure of an offer, but it is not the only one. A higher offer with multiple conditions attached is often less valuable in practice than a lower unconditional offer from a well-qualified buyer. The key variables to assess alongside price are: whether the offer is subject to finance, whether there is a building and pest inspection condition, the settlement date and whether it aligns with your own timing needs, the deposit amount and when it is payable, and any special conditions the buyer has included.</p>

      <p>Finance conditions carry the most risk for sellers. A buyer who is subject to finance approval can withdraw from the contract if their loan is not approved, even after you have taken the property off the market and potentially declined other offers. Pre-approved buyers and those with unconditional finance are meaningfully stronger counterparties. Similarly, a buyer who needs a 90-day settlement because they have not yet sold their existing home introduces a different kind of risk from one who can settle in 30 days with a clear title.</p>

      <p>It is also worth considering buyer profile in situations where the property has emotional significance or where you are choosing between genuinely comparable offers. Owner-occupiers who intend to live in and maintain the property are a different consideration from investors, particularly in circumstances where settlement risks and post-settlement outcomes matter to you.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers typically regret</h2>
      <p>The most common regret in multi-offer situations is signing too quickly with the first offer without giving other interested buyers a genuine opportunity to compete. This happens most often when a seller is anxious to lock in a result or when an agent fails to communicate clearly that other buyers are close to submitting. Taking an extra 24 to 48 hours to allow competing interest to crystallise rarely costs a sale and frequently improves the outcome.</p>

      <p>The second most common regret is the reverse: running a best and final process that pushes the strongest buyer away. Some buyers, particularly those who have already lost other properties through competitive processes, will decline to participate in what they perceive as an auction by another name. If you have a buyer who is highly motivated and well-qualified, consider whether a direct negotiation might produce a stronger and more reliable outcome than a formal multi-offer process.</p>

      <p>Good agent guidance through a multi-offer situation is where execution matters most. The way competing interest is communicated to buyers, the sequencing of responses, and the judgement calls about when to push for more and when to close are all skills that vary significantly between agents. This is not a situation where process alone produces results.</p>

